# Fixture IRI-004: percent-encoding case sensitivity
#
# RFC 3986 §2.1: percent-encoding sequences are octets written as %XX
# where XX is two hexadecimal digits.  The digits are case-insensitive
# from a URI-equivalence perspective, but RDF Concepts §3.1 defines
# IRI equality as a simple string comparison — no normalization.
#
# Therefore `%c3%a9` and `%C3%A9` (both encode the UTF-8 sequence for
# U+00E9 LATIN SMALL LETTER E WITH ACUTE) are TWO DISTINCT IRIs in RDF.
#
# RFC 3986 §6.2.2.1 recommends normalizing percent-encoding to uppercase
# hex digits.  An implementation that applies this recommendation at
# parse time or storage time will incorrectly UNIFY the two IRIs below,
# creating a spurious merge that corrupts graph identity.
#
# Hypothesis: If an implementation uppercases hex digits in percent
# sequences at any point before comparison, it will treat these two
# subject IRIs as equal and merge their facts — the diff will show zero
# facts on one side (they collapsed) rather than two distinct subjects.
#
# Spec: RFC 3986 §2.1, §6.2.2.1
#       RFC 3987 §3.1 (IRI-to-URI conversion normalizes to uppercase — only for URI form)
#       RDF Concepts §3.1 (IRI equality is string equality)

# Subject A: lowercase percent-encoding  (café)
<http://example/caf%c3%a9> <http://example.org/pred/label> "cafe-lowercase-pct" .

# Subject B: uppercase percent-encoding  (café)
<http://example/caf%C3%A9> <http://example.org/pred/label> "cafe-uppercase-pct" .

# These two triples have DISTINCT subjects in RDF.
# A normalizing parser will merge them into one subject — divergence.
